{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0127ebf0-44e0-11ed-8b9a-28325917f596","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"2e1c2f69-4b1c-406c-bbe2-7c5ff7f1356c","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Hanging on to Losers and the Disposition Effect","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"803c4c89-8c9d-4b01-bcab-f96dd4d8a537"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"6dcd4089-d282-449b-b3be-9e67e4c5761e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Investors tend to hold on to stocks that have lost value and sell stocks that have risen in value since the time of purchase. We call this tendency to keep losers and sell winners the ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"bd1a7a27-aacc-4cb1-bbe0-11dc4aee5739","stage":{"ref":"9c8c9bc2-66db-41ad-abb2-b2e8247bb361","sections":[{"ref":"b89895e3-09f5-4150-a552-85e763329b61","rows":[{"ref":"ee263f51-d36f-4221-9d95-65401356034a","columns":[{"ref":"3b2ead56-77f8-4eff-ac51-9c2995d93c33","stageElements":[{"ref":"40062cb8-a859-4169-9d3e-e1f8733d5c55","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"27549221-8b44-465a-a4c2-854858d0c155","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"e71f2744-af78-488c-aa20-305cf0ad4ab3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The tendency to hold on to stocks that have lost value and sell stocks that have risen in value since the time of purchase.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"disposition effect","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"2fb9509a-da88-4081-b965-33388647459a"},{"object":"text","text":". Researchers Hersh Shefrin and Meir Statman, building on the work of psychologists Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky, suggest that this effect arises due to investors’ increased willingness to take on risk in the face of possible losses.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"c842eccf-9996-4e5a-bba2-eb223bdf3c05","stage":{"ref":"54a2e347-21e2-4b79-9912-3ad8a466e531","sections":[{"ref":"d52af556-0d06-4d9a-9e31-9df9ca866b0e","rows":[{"ref":"9cf89a4d-1e34-464e-b792-962eaa57efe9","columns":[{"ref":"ae3cb551-d5f5-4e55-9427-c25c920a2302","stageElements":[{"ref":"46b6fd6a-74b6-4757-83b1-1c65a0d04074","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"9ab7e667-2eda-45bb-a506-9982bc9db05c","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"860b9f12-1973-45e4-8467-2b7278772b44","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"H. Shefrin and M. Statman, “The Disposition to Sell Winners Too Early and Ride Losers Too Long: Theory and Evidence,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Finance","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 40 (1985): 777–790, and D. Kahneman and A. Tversky, “Prospect Theory: An Analysis of Decision under Risk,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Econometrica","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":", 47 (1979): 263–291.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"5","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"bc49ad55-29c9-4640-9cde-4404a589a7a7"},{"object":"text","text":" It may also reflect a reluctance to admit a mistake by taking the loss.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"bfdd8100-cde9-42df-81ca-458960f4ef68"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f5f97996-1acf-42a2-abba-9fa93eb67d70","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Researchers have verified the disposition effect in many studies. For example, in a study of all trades in the Taiwanese stock market from 1995–1999, investors in aggregate were twice as likely to realize gains as they were to realize losses. Also, nearly 85% of individual investors were subject to this bias.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"04a5756b-5ee4-4379-b220-e46a01ea366d","stage":{"ref":"5e96f7fb-a20c-40ce-9d0f-05845a1c6739","sections":[{"ref":"18b35dc7-efc9-4be0-ac8e-5d3958c6b196","rows":[{"ref":"3fdb1ca6-a098-463a-aeb4-f13ea07e4ed7","columns":[{"ref":"4fdd7e81-db8e-46e0-abeb-e3a0d519b8e2","stageElements":[{"ref":"9c785e96-cee7-4c1d-8811-2f4b3c3ee18c","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"f0dba924-57bf-4c87-8aa5-a8ec950811dd","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"e8deaae3-24cb-4fb6-84ba-c2beaed0507d","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"B. Barber, Y. T. Lee, Y. J. Liu, and T. Odean, “Is the Aggregate Investor Reluctant to Realize Losses? Evidence from Taiwan,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"European Financial Management","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 13 (2007): 423–447.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"6","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"f55fc2f0-fd9c-40c4-8dc0-d62b3cf658e6"},{"object":"text","text":" On the other hand, mutual funds and foreign investors did not exhibit the same tendency, and other studies have shown that more sophisticated investors appear to be less susceptible to the disposition effect.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"9ab84d32-d67f-4a71-8749-362d5ae3478d","stage":{"ref":"96829f53-7e57-48ea-91fb-d630a9c1a3a4","sections":[{"ref":"759e59b4-b14a-4b27-a1c3-885b6a4a0ac2","rows":[{"ref":"3550a02f-3408-4e9a-b044-7f3b526d5062","columns":[{"ref":"8b1d34d6-1c24-44c8-890d-51e4a61b79c6","stageElements":[{"ref":"5cf8f330-de82-46d4-9b29-d2e240a259fd","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"cf37bc02-6417-4581-a41d-5191d2db5a45","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"bb816fa2-d76c-4e4d-b15f-582a3873d596","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"R. Dhar and N. Zhu, “Up Close and Personal: Investor Sophistication and the Disposition Effect,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Management Science","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 52 (2006): 726–740.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"7","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"e386f3d3-9ac3-457d-b554-8b2a194d7481"}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"8517f847-8b6e-429f-9a98-de7335d49427"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f4db15ae-8946-4eb5-ad85-a1c8216fdbc3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"This behavioral tendency to sell winners and hang on to losers is costly from a tax perspective. Because capital gains are taxed only when the asset is sold, it is optimal for tax purposes to postpone taxable gains by continuing to hold profitable investments; delaying the tax payment reduces its present value. On the other hand, investors should capture tax losses by selling their losing investments, especially near the year’s end, in order to accelerate the tax write-off.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"e961c98b-9543-4964-bd5f-f64ead016550"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"b938c0c3-b2f1-4157-b7a5-5d566e438f9a","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Of course, keeping losers and selling winners might make sense if investors forecast that the losing stocks would ultimately “bounce back” and outperform the winners going forward. While investors may in fact have this belief, it does not appear to be justified—if anything, the losing stocks that investors continue to hold tend to ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"underperform","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" the winners they sell. According to one study, losers underperformed winners by 3.4% over the year after the winners were sold.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"736a541f-31cb-427c-b8e0-74b593073ef0","stage":{"ref":"64455790-65ff-40de-a53c-1fab661d80fa","sections":[{"ref":"45d15889-a371-4bab-be54-f77ebbb110d0","rows":[{"ref":"378a0434-f4aa-441e-b84f-0482e8ff17b7","columns":[{"ref":"a8481eab-e1d3-4f1a-95a2-7b785610e4a0","stageElements":[{"ref":"62d496b1-5997-4e39-b583-0a5ab0bf235c","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"f9fdb2d3-28ee-4b87-835c-024e7d0e787c","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"a62e385d-6f21-4954-8e61-62acc43a09b7","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"T. Odean, “Are Investors Reluctant to Realize Their Losses?” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Finance","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 53 (1998): 1775–1798.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"8","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"81d39b1b-128d-41c6-b972-6888ac3760ff"}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"f124eb4d-8b70-4976-ae31-e2f5d9f90fec"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,